sec.p:
Once the dynamic stiffness matrix is known the frequencies of vibration may be obtained by means of the Wittrick and Williams algorithm (Williams and Wittrick, 1970). The algorithm evaluates the number J of frequencies of vibration which are lower than a trial value ω* and, therefore, by means of an iteration procedure, to converge to any required frequency. This number may be expressed as
(34)J=Jk+J0
where Jk may be evaluated in one of the following equivalent ways:


as the number of negative signs on the leading diagonal elements of the upper triangular matrix formed from the structure dynamic stiffness matrix by the usual form of Gauss elimination when evaluated at the specified frequency value ω*;

as the number of negative eigenvalues of the dynamic stiffness matrix evaluated at the specified frequency value ω*;

as the number of changes of sign between consecutive members of the Sturm sequence of the minors of order increasing from 0 to the order of the matrix

The exact obtained results confirm the conclusions previously derived by other authors by considering approximate methods (Yokoyama, 1996; Matsunaga, 1999). Namely the following main aspects can be emphasized:


the effect of shear deformability and rotational inertia are more important for the beam resting on an elastic medium rather than for the beam non interacting with the soil;

the natural frequencies of thin cross section beams or squat beams are greatly over-predicted by the classical Bernoulli-Euler theory; therefore it is extremely important to take into account both the rotational inertia and the shear deformability effects for these type of beams.
